Task.Name: Read this item to understand the context of the template
Task.Notes:
This template should help the bride and groom-to-be with organization of all of the details that are involved in planning and executing a beautiful wedding. There are no specific estimates of duration; all activities are left at the default level of one day. The activities identified provide the major components involved in planning a wedding but is not intended to be all-inclusive. The activities and time frames will need to be adjusted based on the formality of the wedding.
This template is a bit different than the typical business template in the way it is structured: Rather than set up phases or stages that have a progressive order, this schedule is organized by major components. Within each component, the activities are identified in a more-or-less chronological order. It includes some time-related phases because there is a great deal of lead time needed to schedule certain critical components. Because of these lead times, there will be a significant amount of "lag time" in the schedule. Resources will not work on this schedule in a full-time capacity as they would on a business project. The effort associated with specific activities will not establish a 'critical path' as you would expect in a normal business project. This template is not activity-driven as is the case with most project schedules. The "activities" are often decisions rather than work that needs to be done.

Task.Name: Wedding day goals, contracts, and budget
Contract with Family
Task.Notes:
This section of the template is intended to help the bride, groom, and their families set up appropriate guidelines to have a memorable wedding that is enjoyable and does not cause extreme anxiety or budget overruns for anyone involved.
Expectations should be set with the goal of experiencing a wonderful, memorable event. All activities within the schedule should support that goal. When the wedding day arrives, it is much more important that the friends and family are able to enjoy the day than that all of the minor details are perfect. If the family remembers this goal when they begin, it will be easier to make decisions on all of the details. It will also make all of the planning and preparations much more enjoyable.

Task.Name: Discuss a budget and the size and style of the wedding. Decide who pays for what
Plan health and beauty preparations (nails, diet, hair, skin care and makeup)
Task.Notes: Planning a wedding is very stressful. The purpose of this activity is to make sure that the bride and groom and their friends and family stay healthy and look their best for the big day.

Task.Name: Set the date and the venue
Set the date in meeting with clergy member; schedule pre-marital counseling
Reserve wedding and reception sites; make initial catering contacts
Task.Notes: This activity will drive all of the remaining decisions and planning so it is essential that these items are resolved at least six months before the wedding date.

Task.Name: Select the attendants (bridesmaids and groomsmen)
Task.Notes: The attendants will be an important part of the event. They may assist the bride and groom with planning details. Once decided, the attendants and other important family and friends should be asked to help with the wedding. If they agree, they can be assigned as 'resources' to the activities on this schedule.

Task.Name: Select one usher for every 50 guests
Choose wedding rings
Task.Notes: Some couples decide that they wish to have a custom design for their rings. If this is the case, it should be planned at least six months prior to the wedding.

Task.Name: Complete all honeymoon plans. If traveling outside the country, check on visas, passports and inoculations.
6 Months +
Task.Notes:
We have added a summary task for many sections of the schedule to highlight the importance of advance planning for a wedding. Normal critical path schedules may not be as effective for this type of project because the activities only takes a short amount of time to complete but must be done months ahead of time. There is a great deal of lag time between activities.
We have chosen to keep this template fairly simple and have added lag only at the summary task level. For example, the activities that should happen 3 months before the wedding are noted with a predecessor of the 6 month summary task and a lag of 60 business days. This is not a perfect solution but allows the wedding planners to see that the dates for activities are roughly three months apart.
